The general structure of nitrogen-doped graphene (N-G) is given in Fig.1
                      [45].N-G has three major types of bonding configurations: (i)graphitic N where nitrogen heteroatoms are substituted on inner surface of graphene in hexagonal ring, (ii) pyrollic, and (iii) pyridinic where both are found at edge defects which donate two and one p electrons to π system respectively. Hybridization of pyridinic N is sp2 whereas pyrollic N is sp3 hybridized.Doping of nitrogen has two main challenges viz. precise controlling the content of doping and type of nitrogen in obtaining N-G and their subsequent effect on the reactivity.Bonding state of nitrogen precursor has a significant effect on the selectivity and the catalytic activity of N-G. For example, annealing of GO with ammonia results in pyridinic N and annealing of polymer composite results in pyridinic and pyrrolic N moieties.The nitrogen content in graphene determines the electrocatalytic activity of the catalyst leading to limiting current density.The pyridinic N content improves the onset potential for ORR [46]. Nitrogen-doped quantum dots (N-GQDs) possess a distinct structure (Fig. 2
                     ). In structure, quasi-spherical nanoparticles consist crystalline and amorphous parts [47].

Fourier transfer infrared (FTIR) and X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy techniques demonstrated reduction of epoxy and carbonyl groups during the hydrothermal treatment [136]. Oxidation of graphene sheets in ammonia solution yielded amino functional group in the edge site of GQDs [138, 139]. GQDs can also be prepared by carbonizing organic precursor by applying a thermal treatment. This treatment allowed the morphological control and proper size distribution of the product formed. Water soluble GQDs were synthesized by carbonizing aqueous solution of glucose, an organic precursor. Glucose was heated to 250 °
                           C on a hot plate and changes in colors from colorless to yellow to orange were observed. This mixture was treated with NH3 solution in order to form functionalized GQDs (see Fig. 10
                           )[140].
